<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="242" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[153,1038,693,901]" pageId="5" pageNumber="242">
There are only two species of 
<taxonomicName box="[472,553,731,755]" class="Insecta" family="Sepsidae" genus="Saltella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[472,553,731,755]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="242">Saltella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
recorded for Switzerland, but 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Sepsidae" genus="Saltella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sphondylii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="242">Saltella sphondylii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in particular is quite common on cow pastures. Both species are usually associated to old, dry cow dung pads. In 
<taxonomicName box="[550,631,789,813]" class="Insecta" family="Sepsidae" genus="Saltella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[550,631,789,813]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="242">Saltella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
,the medial and the basal radial wing cells are fused. In contrast to most other black scavenger flies, 
<taxonomicName box="[836,919,819,843]" class="Insecta" family="Sepsidae" genus="Saltella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[836,919,819,843]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="242">Saltella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an unusually dull habitus such that specimens are sometimes mistaken for members of other families.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
